# SwiftUI Development Guidelines

## Expertise and Code Quality
- Expert-level Swift and SwiftUI development
- Focus on latest August/September 2024 documentation and features
- Write clean, maintainable, and efficient code
- Keep descriptions short and concise
- Preserve all existing comments

## UI Design Rules

### Components
- Use native SwiftUI elements (List, NavigationView, TabView, SF Symbols)

### Layout
- Utilize VStack, HStack, ZStack for view composition
- Use Spacer and Padding for proper spacing
- Implement LazyVGrid and LazyHGrid for grid layouts
- Use GeometryReader for dynamic layouts

### Visual Enhancements
- Implement shadows, gradients, and blurs thoughtfully
- Use custom shapes where appropriate
- Add smooth animations for state changes

### Interaction
- Include meaningful gestures
- Provide haptic feedback
- Ensure clear navigation
- Make elements responsive

### Accessibility (Critical)
- ALWAYS use Label instead of accessibilityLabel for buttons with icons
  ```swift
  // ✅ Do this:
  Button(action: { }) {
      Label("Star button", systemImage: "star.fill")
          .labelStyle(.iconOnly)
  }

  // ❌ Don't do this:
  Button(action: { }) {
      Image(systemName: "star.fill")
  }
  .accessibilityLabel("Star button")
  ```
- Support Dynamic Type for all text elements
- Ensure sufficient color contrast
- Provide meaningful VoiceOver labels

## Commands
- When asked to "lint": Run `../Scripts/lint.sh`

## Code Style
- Use explicit closure syntax for buttons with multiple closures (action and label)
- Follow SwiftLint rules for consistent code style
- Keep line length under 120 characters
- Use proper accessibility labels and modifiers
